In reconstructing this imperial model, Marsili reinterprets fragmentary official accounts in light of material evidence and noncanonical and recently excavated texts. In bringing to life the courts, battlefields, markets, shrines, and pleasure quarters of early imperial China, Heaven Is Empty provides a postmodern and postcolonial reassessment of "religion" before the arrival of Buddhism and challenges the application of Greco-Roman and Abrahamic systemic, identitary, and exclusionary notions of the "sacred" to the analysis of pre-Christian and non-Western realities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aLiterature : Classics. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Comparative Religion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847203440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438472034423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438472034/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles